- Dad.
- What?

14:29.840 --> 14:32.355
What's the difference
between morals and ethics?

14:33.440 --> 14:36.831
Well, a moral's an idea...
hmm, about right and wrong.

14:38.280 --> 14:42.399
And ethics are how those morals apply
to specific situations,

14:42.480 --> 14:45.314
like it's wrong to kill someone,

14:45.400 --> 14:48.438
but if they're gonna
kill ten other people,

14:48.520 --> 14:49.749
is it okay to kill him?

14:49.840 --> 14:52.799
I don't know why I use killing
as an example, it's very...

14:52.880 --> 14:54.599
Pretty violent, but it's kind of an...

14:55.960 --> 14:59.670
uh, obvious moral.

15:04.720 --> 15:07.189
This... this guy Luke, in my book,

15:07.280 --> 15:11.399
he has really bad morals and ethics.

15:11.480 --> 15:13.631
- Both.
- Huh.

15:13.720 --> 15:15.632
How is he immoral and unethical?

15:17.200 --> 15:19.954
'Cause he's really bad.

15:20.040 --> 15:23.192
He lies to protect himself,
and then he doesn't lie

15:23.280 --> 15:26.432
when he could lie
to not break Lilly's heart.

15:27.440 --> 15:29.318
I understand that.

15:29.400 --> 15:32.040
What do you think he would say
to defend his own choices?

15:33.480 --> 15:34.914
Um...

15:36.280 --> 15:39.910
Uh, well, maybe he feels bad
about lying the first time.

15:41.200 --> 15:43.874
And so he doesn't lie the second time,

15:43.960 --> 15:46.919
even though that would be the right ethic.

15:47.680 --> 15:48.830
Uh-huh.

15:48.920 --> 15:53.995
So he would defend
his choice by saying

15:54.080 --> 15:58.199
that he learned lying was wrong,
so now he wants to always tell the truth.

16:00.000 --> 16:01.195
Okay.

16:01.280 --> 16:03.176
So he would be right morally
but not ethically.

16:03.200 --> 16:04.395
Eat these.

16:11.720 --> 16:13.120
Hey, get down.

16:26.200 --> 16:27.200
Stay here.

16:27.280 --> 16:28.350
- Why?
- Because I said so.

16:28.440 --> 16:30.079
- Stay here.
- Okay.

16:40.200 --> 16:42.874
- Can I help you, sir?
- Oh, Jesus.

16:44.120 --> 16:46.555
I heard some noises from over a ways.

16:46.640 --> 16:49.917
I see. This is my camp.
These are my things.

16:50.000 --> 16:52.390
I didn't know anyone
was back in this part.

16:52.480 --> 16:55.200
I'm not really back here,
I'm just passing through.

16:55.280 --> 16:56.600
Uh-huh.

16:56.680 --> 16:59.376
It's just me and an old army buddy
of mine. He's hunting at the moment.

16:59.400 --> 17:00.595
Uh-huh.

17:05.040 --> 17:06.952
- Can I help you?
- No.

17:07.040 --> 17:08.952
No, I... I'm just pokin' around.

17:09.560 --> 17:10.675
Uh-huh.

17:12.200 --> 17:13.599
And who have we here?

17:16.400 --> 17:18.471
That's my s... This is my son.

17:18.560 --> 17:19.800
Oh, what's your name?

17:19.839 --> 17:20.990
My son, Alex.

17:21.079 --> 17:22.079
Alex.

17:22.160 --> 17:23.560
And how old are you?

17:23.640 --> 17:24.640
- Eleven.
- Just, uh...

17:24.720 --> 17:25.856
- Eleven!
- Yeah, 11.

17:25.880 --> 17:27.359
Well, what are you reading?

17:29.400 --> 17:30.400
Just a book.

17:30.480 --> 17:31.755
It looks good.

17:33.320 --> 17:34.356
Comely boy.

17:36.880 --> 17:38.075
Thanks.

17:41.840 --> 17:43.832
We aren't looking
for any more company, sir.

17:44.840 --> 17:45.840
Yeah, I bet.

17:47.920 --> 17:51.197
Well, I will be on my way then.

17:57.360 --> 18:01.513
Oh, if I see your buddy, I will say hello.

18:09.320 --> 18:10.800
I told you to stay hiding.

18:15.280 --> 18:16.600
Pack your things.

18:17.400 --> 18:19.437
- Are we moving?
- Yes.

18:19.520 --> 18:21.000
- Now?
- Yes.

18:21.120 --> 18:22.793
- 'Cause of him?
- Yes.

18:22.880 --> 18:24.473
He's a doddering old man.

18:25.440 --> 18:27.238
Him and everyone he knows.

18:28.440 --> 18:29.669
Is this a red alert?

18:31.000 --> 18:33.231
No, but I would like to move
sort of quickly.

18:33.320 --> 18:35.256
Why didn't you say I was your son
like we usually do?

18:35.280 --> 18:36.475
I did say you were my son.

18:36.560 --> 18:38.536
Instead of making me hide
and saying you had a buddy?

18:38.560 --> 18:41.997
Okay, Rag, I'll give you an answer to that
when I have some time to think about it.

18:42.080 --> 18:43.878
Right now,
I need you to gather your things.

18:45.360 --> 18:47.296
Rag, I don't know why you came
out of your hiding spot.

18:47.320 --> 18:48.640
You've never done that before.

18:48.720 --> 18:50.960
You've got to listen to my instructions
when I give them.

18:52.760 --> 18:54.831
- Rag?
- Okay.

18:54.920 --> 18:56.560
Now, the answer to your question...

18:56.600 --> 18:59.399
Well, when you asked me the question,
I said, you know,

18:59.480 --> 19:01.392
"Because I said so," and that's not kind,

19:01.480 --> 19:03.392
it's unfair,
you deserve to have an answer.

19:03.480 --> 19:06.234
And I should have given you an answer,
but I couldn't in that moment.

19:07.440 --> 19:08.874
It's okay.

19:09.000 --> 19:10.673
I knew why.

19:10.760 --> 19:12.080
The man?

19:12.160 --> 19:13.833
Yes, the man.

19:13.920 --> 19:17.118
But... Well, yes, the man. Period.

19:17.200 --> 19:20.398
But, anyway, the... the answer to your q...

19:20.480 --> 19:23.473
Rag? Rag?
How do you know where you're going?

19:23.560 --> 19:24.789
Northwest.

19:24.880 --> 19:26.376
I know which direction
we're supposed to be going,

19:26.400 --> 19:28.676
but how do you know
which direction northwest is?

19:28.760 --> 19:30.536
'Cause you told me
a million times and it's really easy...

19:30.560 --> 19:32.256
But if you're looking at your book,
and you're walking,

19:32.280 --> 19:33.714
and you're trying to listen to me,

19:33.800 --> 19:35.496
how do you know you're gonna go
in the right direction?

19:35.520 --> 19:38.536
'Cause it's not that hard to read,
listen, and walk in a straight line.

19:38.560 --> 19:40.472
Really? Okay, show me your compass.

19:50.000 --> 19:51.673
Okay, fine.

20:04.640 --> 20:06.240
Do you think that man was immoral?

20:06.320 --> 20:10.633
Immoral? Um, maybe, but... I don't know.

20:10.720 --> 20:13.792
I don't know him, so I don't know,
and our rule is better safe than sorry.

20:15.520 --> 20:16.954
Well, I don't know anybody.

20:18.200 --> 20:20.032
What do you mean you don't know anybody?

20:22.440 --> 20:23.999
I don't know anybody.

20:25.040 --> 20:26.235
All I know is you.

20:26.320 --> 20:29.074
Well, you knew that...
those boys at the barn

20:29.160 --> 20:30.719
and you knew their father.

20:32.680 --> 20:34.000
Not really.

20:34.080 --> 20:35.594
What do you mean "not really"?

20:35.680 --> 20:37.717
Well, we only knew them for three days.

20:38.440 --> 20:39.440
Well...

20:40.240 --> 20:42.550
Yeah. But, uh...

20:45.200 --> 20:46.680
I mean, well...

20:49.000 --> 20:50.036
you know me.

20:51.560 --> 20:54.519
I don't know what more
you could possibly ask for.

21:04.040 --> 21:05.838
Do you know how much I love you?

21:07.360 --> 21:08.510
To the sun and back.

21:08.600 --> 21:11.195
To the sun and back 30,000 times.

21:11.280 --> 21:14.717
And it's not even our sun.
It's a sun in a distant galaxy.

21:14.800 --> 21:18.760
And we're taking a very slow spaceship.
It takes a very, very long time.

21:18.880 --> 21:20.234
And there's a lot of headwind.

21:22.120 --> 21:23.395
It's quite a trip.

21:24.560 --> 21:26.040
How much do you love me?

21:29.000 --> 21:31.959
Like, to the top of a tree.

21:35.000 --> 21:36.000
What?

21:38.560 --> 21:39.835
What?

21:39.920 --> 21:41.673
And... and back down.

22:11.840 --> 22:13.559
- Dad?
- Yeah, I'm here.

22:13.640 --> 22:15.233
My stomach hurts a little.

23:16.040 --> 23:18.396
Here, can you drink this?

23:20.400 --> 23:22.278
Charcoal? Yeah.

23:25.320 --> 23:27.312
You know, there's a reason
that vomit smells bad.

23:30.080 --> 23:31.275
What we ate?

23:32.480 --> 23:34.915
Uh, well, no, not exactly.

23:35.000 --> 23:36.878
That's part, but I just...

23:36.960 --> 23:38.872
The reason is so that other people

23:38.960 --> 23:42.271
won't go near it and they won't get sick.

23:43.520 --> 23:44.954
That's evolution at work.

23:46.440 --> 23:48.318
Am I gonna die?

23:48.400 --> 23:51.199
No, babe, you always say that,
and you always get better.

23:55.920 --> 23:57.320
You're not gonna die.

23:58.200 --> 24:00.317
Do I have the plague?

24:00.400 --> 24:01.880
No, you don't have the plague.

24:02.000 --> 24:04.310
Do you remember
when I explained immunity to you?

24:04.400 --> 24:05.720
You're immune.

24:05.840 --> 24:07.056
If you were gonna get the plague,

24:07.080 --> 24:09.356
you would have had it
when you were very, very little.

24:10.800 --> 24:12.416
And people vomit for all kinds of reasons,

24:12.440 --> 24:15.638
and all it means is that your body
is doing what it's supposed to do.

24:18.800 --> 24:24.478
I mean, but you got
to get rid of it in the bowl

24:24.560 --> 24:27.234
and not in the tent.

24:27.360 --> 24:29.397
So when you feel like you're gonna vomit,

24:29.480 --> 24:33.076
you have to say,
"I need the bowl, I need the bowl."

24:34.240 --> 24:35.879
Or else get outside.

24:48.640 --> 24:50.120
She's asleep.

24:50.200 --> 24:52.271
No rash, no fever, nothing.

24:53.480 --> 24:55.756
Babe, I don't think
that you should just give up.

24:55.840 --> 24:58.196
It's not giving up, it's just letting go.

24:58.280 --> 24:59.760
Okay.

24:59.840 --> 25:01.194
Well, I don't want you to let go.

25:01.280 --> 25:04.193
Well, I don't wanna die on a cot
in an overcrowded field hospital

25:04.280 --> 25:07.114
being treated to
by volunteers with no cure.

25:07.200 --> 25:09.157
You don't know that.

25:09.240 --> 25:11.152
You don't know that's what's gonna happen.

26:20.520 --> 26:21.715
Can we check it out?

26:21.800 --> 26:23.837
No, somebody could be living there.

26:24.960 --> 26:26.280
Really?

26:27.240 --> 26:29.232
Yes, really.

26:31.040 --> 26:32.474
Doesn't look like it.

26:36.280 --> 26:37.873
There's vines all over it.

26:39.200 --> 26:40.316
Please?

27:33.280 --> 27:34.475
Hello!

28:33.880 --> 28:36.554
Wait here. Take your whistle out.

28:36.640 --> 28:37.915
Okay.

29:18.120 --> 29:20.237
Okay, take off your pack.

29:20.920 --> 29:22.115
You can go up.

30:28.120 --> 30:29.839
There's bedrooms with beds.

30:29.920 --> 30:30.956
I know.

30:31.920 --> 30:33.115
Look at this.

30:36.080 --> 30:37.480
VoilÃ !

30:37.560 --> 30:40.234
This is better than the barn
and the greenhouse.

30:40.320 --> 30:41.959
- You think so?
- Mm-hmm.

30:48.000 --> 30:49.070
Can we stay?

30:49.200 --> 30:50.953
No, this is somebody else's house.

30:51.040 --> 30:52.394
Well, so was the greenhouse.

30:52.480 --> 30:54.073
Not really.

30:54.160 --> 30:56.072
But, Dad, no one's using it.

31:00.200 --> 31:02.317
Rag, I know it would be nice
to be in a house again.

31:02.400 --> 31:05.552
But a house is a place that other people
come to eventually, especially...

31:05.640 --> 31:06.676
So what? It's fine.

31:06.800 --> 31:08.712
...a house like this. It's not fine.

31:11.000 --> 31:14.118
It's just as fine as in the woods.
We saw that guy in the woods...

31:14.200 --> 31:16.816
- It's more likely someone comes across...
- And that was in the middle of nowhere.

31:16.840 --> 31:19.275
It's just as likely that someone
finds us camping there.

31:19.360 --> 31:22.016
We don't know if that man followed us
or if he told someone about us.

31:22.040 --> 31:24.350
- Well, why would he?
- Because he knew.

31:27.160 --> 31:30.995
Also, this is closer to town, which means
that it's closer to other people.

31:31.080 --> 31:33.276
I don't think it's a safe place to be.

31:34.120 --> 31:37.830
Well, we won't be any farther away
from the town if we make a camp.

31:42.400 --> 31:44.631
It is more likely
that someone comes here...

31:45.680 --> 31:48.036
than to some random place in the woods

31:48.120 --> 31:50.191
where we put a tent,
because this is a house.

31:50.280 --> 31:53.671
I'm not gonna be surprised by people
like we were at the greenhouse.

31:55.200 --> 31:57.715
Dad, the house is covered in dust.

31:57.800 --> 31:59.871
That means that no one ever comes here.

32:03.040 --> 32:07.432
If they did,
we could be carefully prepared for it,

32:07.520 --> 32:11.514
and we could leave immediately
like we always do, with the red alert.

32:12.720 --> 32:18.318
And we can play hide-and-seek inside.

32:18.400 --> 32:20.869
And name the different rooms
like at the pond house.

32:41.360 --> 32:42.396
Okay.

32:43.760 --> 32:46.559
- Well, we can stay for a few days.
- For a few days?

32:46.640 --> 32:50.395
- Yeah, for a few days or not at all.
- Okay, fine, for a few days.

32:55.200 --> 32:56.634
- Dad.
- What?

32:56.720 --> 32:58.680
- Did you see that room upstairs?
- Yes, I saw it.

32:58.720 --> 33:00.336
The one with the toys and everything?

33:00.360 --> 33:02.079
I saw it.

34:54.480 --> 34:55.675
Hi.

34:57.800 --> 35:01.840
You are awesome. You are awesome.

35:04.360 --> 35:06.352
Oh, shh. Shh, shh, shh.

35:36.680 --> 35:37.680
Rag?

35:39.120 --> 35:40.270
Rag?

35:41.960 --> 35:44.395
Get your emergency bag,
I'll show you the safe spot.

35:46.640 --> 35:47.640
Hey, Rag.

35:49.240 --> 35:51.152
It all fits.

35:54.320 --> 35:55.595
Wow.

35:58.640 --> 36:01.314
Take that off. Take it off.

36:01.400 --> 36:03.073
Come downstairs.

36:03.160 --> 36:05.072
I wasn't even leaving the room.

36:17.960 --> 36:19.440
Are you kidding me?

36:20.760 --> 36:23.070
Did I just tell you
to take all those clothes off?

36:24.480 --> 36:25.755
Do you think it's a joke?

36:27.640 --> 36:30.109
Rag, I know new clothes are exciting,

36:30.200 --> 36:32.080
but you should know better
than to put those on.

36:32.160 --> 36:34.436
- It's just a jacket.
- It's not just a jacket!

36:35.640 --> 36:37.950
It's got sparkly things all over it!

36:50.960 --> 36:52.553
Rag, hurry up.

36:58.400 --> 36:59.595
Are you sulking?

37:01.120 --> 37:02.600
Are you gonna sulk?

37:04.280 --> 37:06.192
Put it in the hiding spot.

37:17.160 --> 37:21.598
Okay, so where's the emergency bag?

37:21.680 --> 37:23.876
- There.
- And where's there?

37:23.960 --> 37:25.394
In the fallen tree.

37:27.880 --> 37:29.951
Sure are a lot of fallen trees
around here.

37:30.800 --> 37:32.519
What side of the house is it on?

37:33.360 --> 37:34.840
The kitchen side.

39:25.240 --> 39:27.232
What? What? What?

39:27.320 --> 39:29.118
- Dad!
- What, what, what?

39:29.200 --> 39:30.554
Tell me! What?

39:42.680 --> 39:44.239
Is that a child?

39:46.560 --> 39:49.997
I think it's a mother and a daughter,
but it's hard to tell.

39:50.080 --> 39:51.230
All right.

39:56.360 --> 39:57.794
She's my size.

39:57.880 --> 39:59.473
Don't look at them too much.

39:59.560 --> 40:00.755
It's okay.

40:41.600 --> 40:43.637
Hi. Want some water?

40:45.040 --> 40:46.235
Yes.

40:59.440 --> 41:00.999
What are you thinkin'?

41:04.160 --> 41:06.072
When do you think they died?

41:06.160 --> 41:07.719
Seven or eight years ago.

41:09.760 --> 41:11.513
How old would the kid be?

41:12.680 --> 41:14.592
Maybe 18 years old.

41:18.280 --> 41:19.794
They were like...

41:20.800 --> 41:22.075
skeletons.

41:23.280 --> 41:24.953
They were like skeletons.

41:27.480 --> 41:29.711
But that won't be us anytime soon.

41:30.640 --> 41:31.869
How do you know?

41:33.040 --> 41:37.432
Well, because... we're not gonna get sick.

41:38.480 --> 41:40.756
And because we have long lives to live.

41:44.760 --> 41:48.913
Then why do we have to have
all the red alerts and...

41:49.000 --> 41:51.196
Just because people
aren't getting sick anymore

41:51.320 --> 41:54.233
doesn't mean that the world
is completely...

41:55.680 --> 41:56.750
right again.

42:00.600 --> 42:02.080
When will it be right again?

42:03.920 --> 42:05.354
When it's balanced.

42:07.600 --> 42:09.319
When will it be balanced?

42:10.480 --> 42:12.073
When there are more women.

42:14.920 --> 42:16.912
Why can't men keep it balanced?

42:18.240 --> 42:21.677
'Cause they were scared,
and sad, and lonely,

42:21.760 --> 42:24.559
and that made them angry,
and when they were angry,

42:24.640 --> 42:28.600
they lost sight of everything
that was important and good in life.

42:31.440 --> 42:33.238
What's important and good in life?

42:35.400 --> 42:37.471
Well, it's different for everybody.

42:39.800 --> 42:45.319
But I think that love
is most important and good.

42:45.400 --> 42:48.393
Loving other people,
and letting them love you, and...

42:50.520 --> 42:52.352
I think stories are important and good

42:52.440 --> 42:55.319
because they connect us to other people,

42:55.400 --> 42:58.472
and they make the world
seem like a bigger place.

42:59.400 --> 43:00.914
And they're fun to tell.

43:02.440 --> 43:06.514
But not all men are sad,
and lonely, and angry.

43:06.600 --> 43:08.239
No, not all men.

43:09.480 --> 43:13.793
But we don't know who,
it's hard to tell who, so...

43:13.880 --> 43:15.599
We stay away.

43:15.680 --> 43:19.230
Yep, but just for now, not forever.

43:19.320 --> 43:21.152
And you know what?

43:21.240 --> 43:22.993
I kind of like it, just you and me.

43:25.720 --> 43:27.200
Yeah, me too.

43:42.560 --> 43:43.560
Are we leaving?

43:44.440 --> 43:45.590
Hi.

43:51.760 --> 43:52.760
No.

43:53.760 --> 43:55.353
So, we're staying?

43:55.440 --> 43:57.511
We can stay a little bit longer.

43:57.600 --> 43:59.592
- Then what are you doing?
- I'm storing.

43:59.680 --> 44:00.830
Why?

44:00.920 --> 44:03.000
We don't leave our belongings
sitting around at camp.

44:03.040 --> 44:05.236
We're not gonna leave 'em
sitting around in the house.

44:06.960 --> 44:09.395
So get your belongings together.

44:12.040 --> 44:14.077
Put them in storage, get your day pack.

44:15.840 --> 44:17.911
And please put on your own clothes.

44:18.000 --> 44:20.469
- Where are we going?
- We're going to town.

44:21.240 --> 44:23.436
- Really?
- Yes.

44:23.520 --> 44:25.239
Are we going all the way to the shed?

44:25.320 --> 44:26.436
No.

44:26.520 --> 44:28.637
- The library?
- If we can.

44:28.720 --> 44:31.030
If we aren't going to the library,
I wanna stay here.

44:31.120 --> 44:35.637
Rag, please put on your town hat
and take off the jacket.

44:36.440 --> 44:39.990
I'm not walking there,
and I'm not wearing that stupid hat.

44:40.080 --> 44:42.056
You know,
there are some things you get to decide

44:42.080 --> 44:43.992
and there are some things that you don't.

44:44.080 --> 44:45.480
Well, what do I decide?

44:45.560 --> 44:47.576
You get to decide what kinda attitude
you're gonna have

44:47.600 --> 44:49.831
when you have to do things
that you don't wanna do.

46:07.960 --> 46:09.155
He's young.

46:09.240 --> 46:11.960
Yeah, he was just a newborn
when it happened.

46:13.320 --> 46:15.551
Well, it's nice
to see a little guy around.

46:15.640 --> 46:16.640
Uh-huh.

46:16.720 --> 46:19.030
Probably not the youngest anymore.

46:19.120 --> 46:22.192
They're making little girl babies
in a laboratory in California.

46:22.280 --> 46:24.590
Probably a lot more in China.

46:24.680 --> 46:27.479
Hey, you like little yellow China dolls?

46:28.720 --> 46:30.598
Is that a "no"? You're shy, aren't you?

46:30.680 --> 46:33.216
He hasn't made up his mind yet.
Thank you very much.

46:33.240 --> 46:34.310
No worries.

47:58.320 --> 47:59.595
How tall am I?

48:01.000 --> 48:02.673
Hmm, seven or eight feet.

48:03.840 --> 48:04.956
Really.

48:05.840 --> 48:07.320
Four feet, nine inches.

48:09.680 --> 48:11.751
My legs aren't long enough.

48:11.840 --> 48:13.911
Well, what makes you say that?

48:14.000 --> 48:16.560
A woman's legs are supposed
to be half her body length.

48:17.360 --> 48:18.430
Uh, what?

48:18.520 --> 48:19.920
That's what it said in the news.

48:20.040 --> 48:21.440
What news?

48:21.520 --> 48:22.670
This.

48:27.280 --> 48:29.158
Did you get this from the library?

48:29.240 --> 48:30.515
Yeah.

48:30.600 --> 48:32.990
Those magazines are full of lies, kid.

48:33.080 --> 48:36.869
They lie about who people are
and what they're supposed to be like.

48:36.960 --> 48:38.360
But it said "scientists say."

48:38.440 --> 48:39.896
Anybody can call themself a scientist,

48:39.920 --> 48:42.913
and anyone can write anything
they want in a magazine.

48:43.000 --> 48:45.799
Do you know how long a woman's legs
are really supposed to be?

48:45.880 --> 48:48.111
- How long?
- Long enough to reach the ground.

48:50.320 --> 48:51.549
Do your legs reach the ground?

48:51.640 --> 48:52.640
Yeah.

48:54.480 --> 48:55.914
Well, then they're perfect.

49:06.160 --> 49:08.320
When we were in town
and that man asked you a question,

49:08.360 --> 49:10.238
did you know what he was talking about?

49:12.280 --> 49:13.316
Sort of.

49:21.560 --> 49:23.677
Babies aren't grown in laboratories.

49:34.960 --> 49:36.838
They are made, uh...

49:38.120 --> 49:40.191
when a man and a woman,

49:40.280 --> 49:42.590
who love each other,

49:42.680 --> 49:45.514
uh, put their bodies together
in a special way

49:45.600 --> 49:47.717
and it makes the woman pregnant.

49:47.800 --> 49:48.995
Sex.

49:52.920 --> 49:54.639
Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm.

49:59.640 --> 50:01.757
Was that something
that you read about in a book?

50:01.840 --> 50:03.672
Mm-hmm. Yeah.

50:05.280 --> 50:07.576
I feel like I should be reading
the books that you're reading,

50:07.600 --> 50:09.478
so I know what kinds of things
you're learning,

50:09.560 --> 50:11.816
because I didn't think that you were
reading books about things like that...

50:11.840 --> 50:12.990
It's fine.

50:14.600 --> 50:15.875
Okay, well...

50:17.000 --> 50:18.480
Did this book, uh...

50:21.320 --> 50:25.439
Anyway, uh, it's just science.

50:25.520 --> 50:28.558
So I'll just explain it,
because it's not that big of a deal.

50:28.640 --> 50:33.590
So, uh, babies are made by,
uh, men and women who are in love.

50:33.680 --> 50:36.559
And they, uh, put their bodies together

50:36.640 --> 50:38.996
in a special way,
'cause they're all grown up.

50:39.080 --> 50:43.393
And, um, that results in a baby

50:43.480 --> 50:45.949
growing in the woman's belly.

50:53.320 --> 50:58.031
And a baby grows for 40 weeks or so

50:58.120 --> 51:00.794
in, uh, a womb.

51:00.880 --> 51:02.519
Uh, it's called a "womb,"

51:02.600 --> 51:05.434
which is a nice safe place
for a baby to grow.

51:05.520 --> 51:08.080
Uh, and that's in a woman's belly.

51:08.160 --> 51:14.316
And then it comes out
of her, uh, vagina, and, um...

51:17.080 --> 51:20.152
Um, so those are body parts
that you have too.

51:20.240 --> 51:23.472
Uh, but you're a child,
and so they're different.

